This paper deals with the security aspect of PowerShell, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). It also involves the use of .NET and runtime hijacking techniques, which are related to software engineering (cs.SE) and programming languages (cs.PL). The paper also discusses the monitoring and prevention of attacks, which can be related to systems and control (cs.SY) and distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC).
